\begin{abstract}
% ==============================================================
Traditional educational assessments fail to capture the true ability of learners by presenting identical questions regardless of individual competency levels. This paper presents \textbf{ShopSphere Adaptive Assessment}, an Adaptive Multi-Agent MCQ Difficulty Prediction System that dynamically evaluates student responses and adjusts question difficulty in real time using a fully LLM-driven pipeline. Building upon the multi-agent competency-building framework of Outay~\textit{et~al.}~\cite{outay2024}, we adapt the Assess--Predict--Oversee--Transit (APOT) model to a question-based adaptive testing context, reinterpreting its original agents---the Learning Style Assessment Agent (LSAA), Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent (SOLMA), Stage of Learning Prediction Agent (SOLPA), and Stage of Learning Transition Agent (SOLTA)---as LLM-powered reasoning modules rather than deterministic formula-driven components. The system is orchestrated through the CrewAI multi-agent framework, deploying three specialized agents powered by Google Gemini 2.5 Flash: an \textit{MCQ Evaluator Agent} (implementing SOLMA), a \textit{Difficulty Predictor Agent} (implementing SOLPA), and an \textit{Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent} (implementing SOLTA), while the overarching assessment context and learning-style-aware question generation embody the LSAA function. Each agent reasons over student answer correctness and response time to collaboratively determine the difficulty level of the current question and recommend the most appropriate difficulty for the next question. A dual-layer architecture ensures UI responsiveness through synchronous rule-based fallback while a background multi-agent pipeline provides richer AI-driven analysis. The system eliminates reliance on pre-calibrated Item Response Theory (IRT) models and static threshold formulas, instead leveraging the contextual reasoning capabilities of large language models to produce transparent, flexible, and explainable adaptive assessments. A design-level analysis demonstrates the logical consistency of the agent collaboration pipeline, the correctness of the adaptive difficulty rules, and the qualitative responsiveness of the system to diverse student performance patterns across three cognitive domains: Reasoning, Aptitude, and Verbal Ability.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
adaptive assessment, MCQ difficulty prediction, multi-agent system, CrewAI, Gemini, LLM-based adaptation, competency analysis, personalized assessment, APOT model
