\section{Related Work}
% ==============================================================

\subsection{Multi-Agent Systems in Education}

Multi-Agent Systems (MAS) have gained significant attention in educational technology due to their ability to model complex, distributed, and intelligent behaviors~\cite{wooldridge2009}. Outay~\textit{et~al.}~\cite{outay2024} proposed the APOT model, which leverages a MAS architecture to manage different stages of competency development. Their system introduces four specialized agents, each responsible for a specific aspect of the learning process:

\begin{itemize}
    \item The \textbf{Learning Style Assessment Agent (LSAA)}, which evaluates the learner's preferred learning modality and adapts content presentation accordingly.
    \item The \textbf{Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent (SOLMA)}, which continuously monitors the learner's current performance and progress indicators.
    \item The \textbf{Stage of Learning Prediction Agent (SOLPA)}, which predicts the learner's potential and forecasts difficulty based on observed performance patterns.
    \item The \textbf{Stage of Learning Transition Agent (SOLTA)}, which determines when and how to transition the learner to the next stage of competency based on accumulated evidence.
\end{itemize}

These agents collaboratively compute a Learning Index (LI) and Competency Index (CI) to monitor learner progress across sessions. However, their framework targets vocational training in AR environments, limiting its direct applicability to digital, question-based assessment contexts~\cite{outay2024}. Our work adapts the APOT's multi-agent collaboration philosophy to a question-driven setting, replacing quantitative KPIs with LLM-based reasoning over correctness, time, and difficulty trajectory.

\subsection{Computerized Adaptive Testing}

Computerized Adaptive Testing (CAT) has been extensively studied since the 1970s and is widely regarded as a robust method for personalized assessment~\cite{weiss2004}. CAT systems typically rely on IRT, where each question is associated with parameters such as difficulty, discrimination, and guessing probability~\cite{lord1980}. While statistically rigorous, IRT-based CAT systems require large, well-calibrated item banks that are expensive and time-consuming to develop~\cite{hambleton1985}. The probabilistic nature of IRT models also makes them difficult to interpret for educators. Our approach replaces IRT with LLM-based agents that reason over observable performance signals---correctness and time---using transparent natural language rules, offering ease of deployment without sacrificing adaptive responsiveness.

\subsection{LLM-Augmented Assessment Frameworks}

Recent advances in Large Language Models have enabled their integration into educational systems for tasks such as feedback generation, tutoring, and content creation~\cite{chen2023}. Multi-agent orchestration frameworks such as CrewAI and AutoGen~\cite{liang2023} facilitate the deployment of LLM-augmented systems where agents collaborate to perform complex reasoning tasks. Bloom's taxonomy~\cite{bloom1956} provides a cognitive hierarchy that informs how question difficulty scales with learner ability; our three-level difficulty scheme (Easy, Medium, Hard) is grounded in this framework. Unlike prior hybrid systems that restrict LLMs to feedback generation only, our system delegates the full assessment pipeline---including answer evaluation, difficulty prediction, and adaptation decision---to LLM agents, demonstrating that prompt-engineered agents can reliably implement psychometric adaptation logic without deterministic formulas.

\subsection{Reinforcement Learning and Adaptive Education}

Reinforcement learning (RL) approaches to adaptive education model the problem as a sequential decision-making task, where the system selects the next question to maximize long-term learning outcomes~\cite{sutton2018}. While RL offers theoretical optimality guarantees, it requires extensive training data and reward function design, and its decision-making is opaque to educators. Similarly, Bayesian student models~\cite{conati2002} provide probabilistic tracking of student knowledge but demand careful prior specification. Our LLM-based approach offers an alternative that requires no training phase, operates transparently through natural language reasoning, and can be adapted by modifying agent prompts rather than retraining models.

