\section{System Architecture}
% ==============================================================

\subsection{Assessment Workflow Overview}

The adaptive MCQ difficulty prediction system follows a per-question adaptive loop. For each question presented to the student, the system captures the student's selected answer and the time taken to respond. These inputs are passed to the CrewAI pipeline, which executes three agents sequentially. The MCQ Evaluator Agent (SOLMA) first determines whether the answer is correct or incorrect. The Difficulty Predictor Agent (SOLPA) then classifies the difficulty of the current question based on correctness and time. The Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent (SOLTA) synthesizes these results to output both the current question's difficulty classification and the recommended difficulty level for the next question. This loop repeats for each of the 20~questions in the session, enabling real-time adaptation of assessment difficulty.

\subsection{Layered Architecture}

The system is organized into five interconnected layers, each with clearly defined responsibilities:

\textbf{1) Presentation Layer.} Implemented as Django HTML templates with Bootstrap~5.3, this layer handles question display, answer input collection, and timer visualization. A fullscreen enforcement gate using the browser Fullscreen API ensures assessment integrity, while \texttt{navigator.sendBeacon} provides graceful auto-submission on tab closure.

\textbf{2) Controller/Orchestration Layer.} Django views coordinate the test lifecycle: session initialization, answer processing, skip-question management, timer enforcement, and result compilation. This layer implements the synchronous rule-based difficulty fallback and spawns the asynchronous agent pipeline.

\textbf{3) AI/Agent Pipeline Layer.} The CrewAI multi-agent pipeline executes in a background daemon thread, running the three APOT-mapped agents (SOLMA, SOLPA, SOLTA) sequentially. This layer communicates with the Gemini~2.5 Flash LLM and produces structured difficulty analysis.

\textbf{4) Question Generation Layer.} A dedicated module invokes Google Gemini via the \texttt{google-generativeai} SDK to generate MCQs on-the-fly at the specified difficulty level, eliminating dependence on a static question bank.

\textbf{5) Data/Persistence Layer.} Three MySQL-backed Django models---\texttt{StudentTestResult}, \texttt{QuestionPerformance}, and \texttt{AdaptiveLearningHistory}---provide durable storage for test sessions, per-question AI analysis, and difficulty progression tracking.

\subsection{APOT Model Adaptation}

The original APOT learning model~\cite{outay2024} follows a cyclic process of Assess, Predict, Oversee, and Transit stages managed by the LSAA, SOLMA, SOLPA, and SOLTA agents. In our adaptation:

\begin{itemize}
    \item The \textbf{Assess} stage maps to the MCQ Evaluator Agent, which implements the \textbf{SOLMA} (Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent) function by determining answer correctness and monitoring the student's immediate performance.
    \item The \textbf{Predict} stage maps to the Difficulty Predictor Agent, which implements the \textbf{SOLPA} (Stage of Learning Prediction Agent) function by classifying the current question's difficulty using psychometric heuristics.
    \item The \textbf{Oversee} and \textbf{Transit} stages jointly map to the Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent, which implements the \textbf{SOLTA} (Stage of Learning Transition Agent) function by synthesizing prior analyses and determining the appropriate difficulty transition.
    \item The \textbf{LSAA} (Learning Style Assessment Agent) function is embodied by the overarching assessment design: topic-aware question generation across three cognitive domains (Reasoning, Aptitude, Verbal Ability) and the domain-specific prompt engineering that tailors question content to each domain's characteristics.
\end{itemize}

