\subsection{Dual-Layer Difficulty Adaptation}

A key architectural innovation is the dual-layer difficulty adaptation mechanism that decouples UI responsiveness from the heavier multi-agent LLM pipeline:

\textbf{Synchronous Layer (Rule-Based Fallback).} When the student submits an answer, the controller immediately applies a deterministic rule-based mapping to compute the next difficulty:
\begin{equation}
d_{n+1} = 
\begin{cases}
f_{\uparrow}(d_n) & \text{if answer is correct} \\
f_{\downarrow}(d_n) & \text{if answer is incorrect}
\end{cases}
\label{eq:sync_rules}
\end{equation}
where $f_{\uparrow}$: Easy$\rightarrow$Medium, Medium$\rightarrow$Hard, Hard$\rightarrow$Hard and $f_{\downarrow}$: Hard$\rightarrow$Medium, Medium$\rightarrow$Easy, Easy$\rightarrow$Easy. The next question is immediately generated at this difficulty and returned in the HTTP response, ensuring sub-second UI updates.

\textbf{Asynchronous Layer (Multi-Agent AI Pipeline).} In parallel, a daemon thread executes the full SOLMA$\rightarrow$SOLPA$\rightarrow$SOLTA CrewAI pipeline. When complete, the richer AI-derived analysis---including predicted difficulty, reasoning, and recommendations---is persisted to the \texttt{QuestionPerformance} and \texttt{AdaptiveLearningHistory} tables, and the \texttt{StudentTestResult.final\_difficulty} is updated. This design ensures that detailed AI insights are always recorded for post-assessment analytics without blocking the student's real-time test experience.

\subsection{Dynamic LLM-Driven Question Generation}

Rather than drawing from a static question bank, the system generates each question on-the-fly by prompting Google Gemini 2.5 Flash with the target topic, difficulty level, and question number. The prompt enforces a strict JSON schema:

\begin{verbatim}
{
  "id": <question_number>,
  "question": "<text>",
  "options": ["A", "B", "C", "D"],
  "correct_answer": "<exact option>",
  "explanation": "<reasoning>"
}
\end{verbatim}

This eliminates the need for pre-curated item banks---a key limitation of traditional IRT-based systems~\cite{lord1980}---and enables the system to generate an unlimited variety of questions at any difficulty level across the three supported cognitive domains. Topic normalization ensures controlled vocabulary: \textit{reasoning}, \textit{aptitude} (with aliases: quantitative aptitude, quant), and \textit{english} (with aliases: verbal, verbal ability). Retry logic with exponential backoff handles transient API failures (503, 429, 500), and a stub fallback question is returned if all retries fail.

