\section{Multi-Agent Framework}
% ==============================================================

The multi-agent architecture distributes the adaptive assessment task across three specialized agents, each mapped to an APOT agent role and defined with a distinct \texttt{role}, \texttt{goal}, and \texttt{backstory} in the CrewAI framework. All agents are powered by Google Gemini 2.5 Flash via the CrewAI LLM interface with a temperature of~0.7. The agents execute sequentially with context passed between tasks, ensuring that each agent builds upon the output of its predecessor.

\subsection{MCQ Evaluator Agent (SOLMA --- Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent)}

The \textbf{MCQ Evaluator Agent} serves as the first stage of the pipeline and implements the \textbf{SOLMA} function from the APOT model, corresponding to the \textit{Assess} phase. Just as the original SOLMA agent monitors a learner's current stage and performance indicators~\cite{outay2024}, our MCQ Evaluator Agent monitors the student's immediate response quality.

Its role is strictly defined as a fair and accurate MCQ examiner: given the question text, the correct answer, and the student's selected answer, it determines whether the response is correct or incorrect and provides a one-line explanation. The agent is configured with \texttt{allow\_delegation=False} to ensure it does not offload this factual judgment to other agents.

The agent's task receives a structured input block containing:
\begin{itemize}
    \item The question text
    \item The correct answer
    \item The student's selected answer
    \item The time taken in seconds
\end{itemize}

Its expected output is a binary correctness verdict with a brief justification, providing the factual foundation for subsequent agents. This isolation of correctness determination from difficulty reasoning ensures that the monitoring function remains objective and independently auditable.

\subsection{Difficulty Predictor Agent (SOLPA --- Stage of Learning Prediction Agent)}

The \textbf{Difficulty Predictor Agent} implements the \textbf{SOLPA} function from the APOT model, corresponding to the \textit{Predict} phase. In the original framework, SOLPA predicts the learner's potential and forecasts performance trajectories~\cite{outay2024}. Our adaptation reinterprets this predictive role for the question-difficulty domain: the agent predicts the true difficulty of the current question---classified as Easy, Medium, or Hard---based on the correctness verdict from SOLMA and the response time.

The agent's backstory encodes a psychometric heuristic grounded in adaptive testing literature~\cite{weiss2004}:

\begin{quote}
\textit{``Fast + Correct = Easy question. Slow + Correct = Medium. Wrong = Hard.''}
\end{quote}

This design reflects the insight that a student's response time in conjunction with correctness serves as a behavioral proxy for item difficulty. Rather than computing a numeric difficulty parameter as in IRT~\cite{lord1980}, the agent applies this reasoning in natural language, producing an interpretable and auditable prediction. The agent outputs the predicted difficulty level along with its reasoning for the classification. Notably, no hard-coded time thresholds are imposed; the time value is passed verbatim to the LLM, and the agent interprets ``fast'' and ``slow'' contextually, enabling nuanced judgment that rigid numeric boundaries cannot provide.

\subsection{Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent (SOLTA --- Stage of Learning Transition Agent)}

The \textbf{Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent} is the most complex agent in the pipeline and implements the \textbf{SOLTA} function from the APOT model, serving both the \textit{Oversee} and \textit{Transit} phases. In the original framework, SOLTA determines when and how a learner should transition between competency stages~\cite{outay2024}. Our adaptation translates this transition logic into the difficulty-adaptation domain: the agent determines when and how to transition between difficulty levels based on accumulated evidence from SOLMA and SOLPA.

The agent receives the outputs of both prior agents as context and synthesizes them to produce two key decisions: (1)~the confirmed difficulty classification of the current question, and (2)~the recommended difficulty level for the next question.

The agent's backstory encodes an explicit adaptive rule set grounded in the progressive challenge principle~\cite{vygotsky1978} and Bloom's taxonomy~\cite{bloom1956}:

\textbf{If the answer is correct:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Easy $\rightarrow$ Next: Medium (progressive challenge)
    \item Medium $\rightarrow$ Next: Hard (advance to next level)
    \item Hard $\rightarrow$ Next: Hard or Medium (maintain mastery)
\end{itemize}

\textbf{If the answer is incorrect:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Hard $\rightarrow$ Next: Medium (step down one level)
    \item Medium $\rightarrow$ Next: Easy (step down one level)
    \item Easy $\rightarrow$ Next: Easy (stay at same level for confidence building)
\end{itemize}

The agent is configured with \texttt{allow\_delegation=True}, enabling it to consult prior agents if additional clarification is needed. Its output follows a structured natural language format:

\begin{verbatim}
Questions Difficulty: [Easy/Medium/Hard]
Next Question Difficulty: [Easy/Medium/Hard]
Reasoning: [explanation]
Recommendation: [additional actions]
\end{verbatim}

This structured prompt output is then parsed programmatically to extract the difficulty labels for system use.

\subsection{LSAA --- Learning Style Assessment Agent}

The \textbf{Learning Style Assessment Agent (LSAA)} from the APOT model evaluates the learner's preferred learning modality~\cite{outay2024}. While our system does not deploy a discrete LSAA agent within the CrewAI pipeline, its function is distributed across two system components:

\textbf{1) Domain-Aware Question Generation.} The question generation module accepts a \textit{topic} parameter (Reasoning, Aptitude, or Verbal Ability), tailoring the generated MCQ content to the specific cognitive domain. This domain awareness ensures that the assessment adapts not only in difficulty but also in content characteristics appropriate to the learner's chosen domain.

\textbf{2) Multi-Domain Competency Tracking.} The analytics dashboard tracks domain-level accuracy, computes per-domain performance metrics, and identifies the student's weakest domain for targeted feedback. This mirrors the LSAA's role of understanding individual learning profiles and adapting the assessment experience accordingly.

\subsection{CrewAI Orchestration}

The three pipeline agents (SOLMA, SOLPA, SOLTA) are assembled into a \texttt{Crew} with the following configuration:

\begin{verbatim}
Crew(
    agents=[evaluator, predictor, adaptive],
    tasks=[task1, task2, task3],
    process=Process.sequential,
    verbose=False,
    memory=False,
    max_rpm=10
)
\end{verbatim}

Sequential process execution ensures tasks execute in order. Task~3 (SOLTA) explicitly declares \texttt{context=[task1, task2]}, giving the Overseer Agent access to both the SOLMA correctness verdict and the SOLPA difficulty prediction. The \texttt{memory=False} setting ensures stateless per-question operation, and \texttt{max\_rpm=10} enforces API rate compliance. The \texttt{crew.kickoff()} call executes the full pipeline and returns the SOLTA agent's final output, which is parsed to extract the current and next difficulty values.

