% ==============================================================
\section{Methodology}
% ==============================================================

The methodology focuses on the agent prompt design, the adaptive rule encoding, the information flow across APOT stages, and the robustness mechanisms that enable reliable operation under LLM output variability.

\subsection{Input Representation}

For each MCQ response, the system constructs a structured input string passed to the SOLMA agent's task:

\begin{verbatim}
Question: <question text>
Correct Answer: <correct option>
Student Selected Answer: <student option>
Time Taken by Student: <seconds> seconds
\end{verbatim}

This input captures all observable signals available for a single question interaction: factual correctness (determined by comparing answers) and response efficiency (captured by client-side timing via \texttt{Date.now()} differencing). Both signals together constitute the behavioral fingerprint that the APOT pipeline reasons over.

\subsection{Agent Role and Goal Specification}

Each agent's behavior in CrewAI is governed by three natural language fields: \texttt{role}, \texttt{goal}, and \texttt{backstory}. These fields function as the system prompt for the underlying Gemini model, shaping its reasoning approach for each task. The \texttt{role} defines the agent's identity within the APOT pipeline, the \texttt{goal} specifies its objective, and the \texttt{backstory} provides the contextual knowledge and heuristics the agent should apply.

For the SOLPA agent (Difficulty Predictor), the backstory explicitly encodes the time-correctness heuristic: ``Fast + Correct = Easy question. Slow + Correct = Medium. Wrong = Hard.'' This concise rule set mirrors the psychometric intuition behind time-aware adaptive testing~\cite{weiss2004} and eliminates the need for IRT parameter estimation.

For the SOLTA agent (Adaptive Overseer), the backstory encodes the full bidirectional transition table (escalation on success, de-escalation on failure) aligned with the Zone of Proximal Development concept~\cite{vygotsky1978}, ensuring the system keeps students within their optimal challenge zone.

\subsection{Sequential Task Execution and Context Passing}

The sequential process in CrewAI ensures tasks execute in order with outputs from earlier tasks available as context for later ones. Task~3 (SOLTA) explicitly declares \texttt{context=[task1, task2]}, giving the Overseer Agent access to both the SOLMA correctness verdict and the SOLPA difficulty prediction before making its final transition decision. This mirrors the information aggregation role of the SOLTA stage in the APOT model~\cite{outay2024}, where cumulative performance data informs the transition decision.

The information flow across agents can be formalized as:
\begin{align}
\text{SOLMA}(q, a_c, a_s, t) &\rightarrow v \in \{\text{Correct}, \text{Incorrect}\} \label{eq:solma} \\
\text{SOLPA}(v, t) &\rightarrow d_{\text{current}} \in \{E, M, H\} \label{eq:solpa} \\
\text{SOLTA}(v, d_{\text{current}}) &\rightarrow (d_{\text{current}}', d_{\text{next}}) \label{eq:solta}
\end{align}

where $q$ is the question, $a_c$ the correct answer, $a_s$ the student's answer, $t$ the response time, $v$ the correctness verdict, and $d$ the difficulty level.

\subsection{Output Parsing and Robustness}

The SOLTA agent's output is parsed line by line to extract the structured difficulty labels. Lines containing the keywords \texttt{Questions Difficulty:}, \texttt{Next Question Difficulty:}, \texttt{Reasoning:}, and \texttt{Recommendation:} are individually parsed to populate a result dictionary. Default values of ``Medium'' are used as fallbacks if parsing fails, ensuring graceful degradation under LLM output variability. The full raw output is retained as \texttt{full\_analysis} for logging and audit purposes.

Additional robustness mechanisms include:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{API key validation}: On key failure, the pipeline returns a canned \texttt{Medium}/\texttt{Medium} result with reasoning ``Using default difficulty due to API key issue.''
    \item \textbf{Retry logic}: The question generation module retries transient errors (HTTP 503, 429, 500) up to 3~times with exponential-like backoff of $(attempt + 1) \times 2$~seconds.
    \item \textbf{Stub fallback}: If all retries and JSON parsing fail, a stub question is returned to prevent test interruption.
    \item \textbf{Thread-safe DB access}: The background CrewAI thread explicitly closes its thread-local Django database connection in a \texttt{finally} block to prevent connection leaks.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Session Management and Test Integrity}

Each test session is identified by a UUID (\texttt{assessment\_id}) linking the transient session state in \texttt{request.session} with the durable \texttt{StudentTestResult} record. The session stores the dynamically generated questions, current index, answers, skipped indices, difficulty progression, and timer state. Status transitions follow a controlled state machine:

\begin{equation}
\texttt{in\_progress} \xrightarrow{\text{submit}} \texttt{completed} \mid \xrightarrow{\text{beacon}} \texttt{auto\_submitted} \mid \xrightarrow{\text{exit}} \texttt{expired}
\end{equation}

The fullscreen enforcement gate blocks the test UI until the student explicitly enters fullscreen mode. Tab closure triggers \texttt{navigator.sendBeacon} for automatic submission, and an ``Exit'' button sets the status to expired.

A skip-question revisit mechanism allows students to defer questions: skipped indices are stored and revisited after the linear pass completes, interleaving forward progress with deferred-item completion.

