\subsection{Advantages of LLM-Native Adaptation over Formula-Based Approaches}

A key design decision in this system is the delegation of all difficulty reasoning to LLM agents rather than deterministic formulas. This choice offers several advantages:

\textbf{1) Natural Language Maintainability.} The adaptation rules can be expressed and modified entirely in natural language within agent prompts without rewriting scoring code.

\textbf{2) Contextual Nuance.} The agents can incorporate contextual subtlety---such as recognizing borderline cases in time thresholds---that rigid numeric formulas cannot express. SOLPA interprets ``fast'' and ``slow'' contextually rather than through hard-coded second boundaries.

\textbf{3) Explainable Audit Trail.} The full reasoning chain is available in the agent output, providing educators with a natural language explanation for every difficulty decision, directly supporting the explainability goals of the APOT framework~\cite{outay2024}.

\textbf{4) Zero Pre-Calibration.} Eliminating pre-calibrated IRT parameters and static item banks makes the system deployable in any domain without prior item bank construction~\cite{hambleton1985}. Combined with LLM-driven question generation, the system requires only a topic name and difficulty level to operate.

\textbf{5) Extensibility.} Adding new cognitive domains, modifying difficulty levels, or adjusting adaptation aggressiveness requires only prompt edits---no model retraining or parameter re-estimation.

The primary trade-off is the non-determinism inherent in LLM outputs, which means identical inputs may occasionally produce slightly different outputs. This is mitigated by the structured output format enforced through task descriptions, the line-by-line keyword parsing, the hard ``Medium'' defaults on parsing failure, and the synchronous rule-based fallback layer that guarantees deterministic behavior for the real-time question selection path.

