\section{Technology Stack}
% ==============================================================

The system is implemented as a full-stack web application using Django~4.2 (Python) as the web framework with MySQL as the database backend. The multi-agent pipeline is orchestrated through CrewAI~0.28.0, with each agent powered by Google Gemini~2.5 Flash via both the CrewAI LLM wrapper (for agent reasoning) and the \texttt{google-generativeai}~0.3.0 SDK (for MCQ generation). The frontend uses Bootstrap~5.3 with vanilla JavaScript for the interactive test interface, including Fullscreen API integration and \texttt{sendBeacon} for tab-closure handling. Django REST Framework~3.14.0, Channels~4.0.0, Redis~5.0.0, and Celery~5.3.0 are listed as dependencies for future extensibility. Session state is managed through Django's built-in session framework, with durable persistence via three MySQL tables accessible through the Django ORM.

% ==============================================================
\section{Conclusion and Future Work}
% ==============================================================

This paper presented an Adaptive Multi-Agent MCQ Difficulty Prediction System that operationalizes the APOT framework of Outay~\textit{et~al.}~\cite{outay2024} in a fully LLM-driven, question-based adaptive testing context. By mapping the APOT agents---SOLMA (Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent), SOLPA (Stage of Learning Prediction Agent), and SOLTA (Stage of Learning Transition Agent)---to three specialized CrewAI agents powered by Google Gemini~2.5 Flash, the system replaces deterministic scoring formulas and IRT pre-calibration with prompt-engineered LLM reasoning over answer correctness and response time. The LSAA (Learning Style Assessment Agent) function is realized through domain-aware question generation across Reasoning, Aptitude, and Verbal Ability domains.

The dual-layer architecture---combining synchronous rule-based fallback for real-time responsiveness with asynchronous multi-agent AI analysis for rich insights---demonstrates that production-grade adaptive testing can coexist with computationally intensive LLM pipelines. The LLM-driven question generation mechanism further eliminates the traditional bottleneck of pre-curated item bank construction.

The design-level analysis confirms that the three-agent APOT pipeline provides complete coverage of the adaptive transition space, logically consistent behavior across representative performance scenarios, and a natural language audit trail for every difficulty decision. The system demonstrates that LLM-native multi-agent architectures can implement adaptive testing logic that is simultaneously interpretable, deployable without pre-calibrated item banks, and extensible through simple prompt modification.

Future work will focus on:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Conducting user studies with diverse student populations to empirically validate the accuracy of LLM-predicted difficulty labels against expert annotations.
    \item Extending the LSAA function with an explicit learning-style profiling agent that adapts question format (not just content) based on detected learner preferences.
    \item Integrating session-level memory (\texttt{memory=True} in CrewAI) to enable cross-question performance tracking and long-horizon difficulty planning by SOLTA.
    \item Exploring prompt optimization techniques to reduce LLM output variability and improve structured output reliability across the SOLMA, SOLPA, and SOLTA agents.
    \item Comparing LLM-based adaptation decisions against IRT-based ground truth on standardized item banks to quantify agreement rates and identify systematic biases.
    \item Deploying the system in a multi-user concurrent environment with real-time difficulty dashboards for instructors, leveraging the Celery and Redis infrastructure already present in the technology stack.
    \item Extending domain coverage beyond the current three cognitive domains to technical and professional competency areas.
\end{enumerate}

